# PRD: Model Regression Detection System

**Owner:** Mohammed Sohel Patwari (Arise To Ascend)
**Status:** In Progress
**Version:** 2.0 — rebuilt around a learning-first RAG-based SUT

---

## 1. Problem Statement

LLM-powered features degrade silently. A prompt edit, a model version swap, a temperature change, or even a provider updating a model under the hood can drop accuracy, spike latency, or blow up token cost — with zero code-level error to catch it. Most teams find out from user complaints.

There is no CI/CD-equivalent for LLM output quality. This project builds one: an automated pipeline that evaluates an LLM feature against a fixed dataset on every change, scores it across three axes, and alerts on regression.

---

## 2. Goals

- Detect accuracy, latency, and cost regressions in an LLM feature automatically, on every code/prompt/model change.
- Run as part of a CI/CD pipeline (GitHub Actions), not as a manual script.
- Alert the developer via Slack the moment a regression crosses threshold.
- Store historical run data so trends are visible over time, not just pass/fail.
- **Use this build to actually learn RAG internals, embeddings, and eval design — not just wire together APIs.**

## 3. Non-Goals

- Not building a general-purpose eval framework for arbitrary teams (single-user tool, built for one system under test).
- Not covering multi-step/agentic pipeline tracing — that's the separate Failure Forensics project.
- Not optimizing the LLM feature itself past "good enough to evaluate" — this tool measures it, doesn't perfect it.

---

## 4. System Under Test (SUT) — Mini RAG Q&A Bot

**Why the change from a ticket classifier:** a classifier teaches you almost nothing you don't already know. A small RAG system forces you through the exact concepts AI/LLM interview rounds probe — chunking, embeddings, vector similarity, retrieval, grounding. Same build effort, far more resume and interview value. And it directly strengthens your "AI/LLM engineering" specialization claim with a project you can explain end-to-end.

**What it does:**
- Input: a natural-language question.
- Retrieval: find the most relevant chunks from a small local knowledge base.
- Generation: LLM answers the question using only the retrieved chunks (grounded, not from memory).

**Suggested knowledge base (pick one, keep it small — 15-20 short documents/pages):**
- Your own project docs (README files from Kage Trade, ArbWatch, GestureIQ) — genuinely useful and dogfoods your own work.
- A public FAQ set (e.g., a product's help docs) if you want cleaner ground-truth answers.

**Concepts you'll learn building this:**
| Component | Concept |
|---|---|
| Chunking documents | Why chunk size/overlap affects retrieval quality |
| Embedding chunks | Vector representations of text, embedding models |
| Storing vectors | Vector similarity search (cosine similarity), even without a full vector DB |
| Retrieval step | Top-k retrieval, relevance ranking |
| Generation step | Prompt construction with injected context, grounding to reduce hallucination |

**Minimal stack for the SUT (keep this lightweight — it's not the main deliverable):**
- `sentence-transformers` (local, free) to embed chunks and queries
- Plain Python + numpy/`faiss` (or even a plain list + cosine similarity — skip infra for 20 documents) for retrieval
- Anthropic/OpenAI API call for the generation step, with retrieved chunks injected into the prompt

---

## 5. Golden Dataset

- **Format:** JSON, 25–40 rows.
- **Fields per row:**
  - `id`
  - `question`
  - `expected_answer` (reference answer, written by you)
  - `expected_source_chunk_ids` (which document chunks *should* have been retrieved — this lets you evaluate retrieval quality separately from generation quality, a distinction that matters a lot in real RAG eval)
- **Source:** write questions against your own knowledge base docs. Include:
  - Easy direct-lookup questions
  - Questions requiring info from 2 chunks combined
  - Trick questions with no answer in the knowledge base (tests whether the system correctly says "I don't know" instead of hallucinating — this is a real and important eval case)

---

## 6. Scoring Metrics — aligned to the RAGAS standard

These four metrics (context precision, context recall, faithfulness, answer relevancy) are the industry-standard set popularized by RAGAS and used by DeepEval, TruLens, and every major RAG eval platform in 2026. Using this exact terminology — not homemade names — is what makes this project read as "knows the field" rather than "built a script that resembles RAG."

| Metric | Layer | How it's measured | What it catches |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Context Precision** | Retrieval | Of the chunks retrieved, what fraction are actually relevant? (are the right chunks ranked highest) | Bad reranking, noisy retrieval diluting relevant chunks |
| **Context Recall** | Retrieval | Of the info needed to answer, what fraction did retrieval actually surface? | Chunking too coarse/fine, embedding model regressions, missing coverage |
| **Faithfulness** | Generation | Does the answer only contain claims supported by the retrieved context? (LLM-as-judge scores this, or your own trick-question flag as a lightweight proxy) | Hallucination — the single most important RAG failure mode |
| **Answer Relevancy** | Generation | Does the answer actually address the question asked? (semantic similarity between generated answer and reference answer) | Prompt regressions, off-topic generation, model swap side effects |
| **Latency** | System | Wall-clock time per query, end-to-end (retrieval + generation) | Performance regressions |
| **Token Usage / Cost** | System | Prompt + completion tokens from API response, converted to $ | Cost regressions (e.g. context window bloat) |

**Lightweight implementation note:** full RAGAS uses an LLM-as-judge for faithfulness and answer relevancy, which costs extra API calls per eval run. For your MVP, approximate it: use embedding similarity for answer relevancy (cheap, no extra LLM call), and use your trick-question set (questions with no answer in the knowledge base) as a lightweight faithfulness check — if the model answers confidently anyway, that's a faithfulness failure. Mention in the interview that you know the "proper" version uses LLM-as-judge and chose the cheaper proxy deliberately for cost/speed — that's a real engineering tradeoff, not a shortcut you're hiding.

Splitting retrieval metrics from generation metrics is the single most valuable design decision here — it's what separates a real RAG eval from a toy script, and it's the distinction interviewers specifically probe for.

