## 11. Learning Path & Milestones

Each milestone lists what to build **and** what to understand before moving on — don't just copy-paste, be able to explain the "why" for each.

| Day | Build | Learn |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Chunk knowledge base docs, embed with `sentence-transformers`, store vectors in a list/numpy array | How chunking size affects retrieval; what an embedding actually represents |
| 1 | Write retrieval function (cosine similarity, top-k) | Vector similarity search fundamentals |
| 2 | Write generation step: inject retrieved chunks into prompt, call LLM API | Prompt grounding, why RAG reduces (not eliminates) hallucination |
| 2 | Write golden dataset (25-40 Q&A pairs incl. trick questions) | What makes a good eval set — coverage, edge cases, adversarial cases |
| 3 | Eval runner: loop through dataset, capture retrieval + generation + timing + tokens | Instrumentation — measuring a pipeline, not just running it |
| 3 | Scorer: retrieval accuracy, answer similarity, hallucination flag | Precision/recall concepts, semantic similarity scoring |
| 4 | SQLite results store + baseline comparison logic | Designing for historical comparison, not just single-run pass/fail |
| 4 | Slack webhook alerting | Basic webhook integration |
| 5 | GitHub Actions workflow (on-push + nightly cron) | Real CI/CD wiring for a non-traditional (AI) test suite |
| 5 | README + demo: intentionally degrade something (bad prompt, wrong chunk size) and show the system catches it | Proving the system actually detects regressions, not just producing green checkmarks |

~5 days end to end, but day 1-2 (the RAG build) is where most of the actual learning happens — don't rush that part even if it's tempting to skip ahead to the "impressive" CI/CD wiring.

